<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNITA Accepts Government Offer With Amendments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNITA Accepts Government Offer With Amendments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0906210594 Luanda TPA Television Network in Portuguese 
1930 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0906210594 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda TPA Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from Lusaka by correspondent Manuel da Conceicao] </F>
  [Text] The negotiators at the peace talks here in Lusaka 
woke up very early today. No one was on bed by 0600. There was 
intense movement at mediator Alioune Blondin Beye's hotel room. 
First, Alioune Blondin Beye received the leadership of the 
government negotiating team, which included General Kopelipa, 
special envoy of President of the Republic Jose Eduardo dos 
Santos. Gen. Kopelipa arrived here in Lusaka last evening. 
  Then, Alioune Blondin Beye received the leadership of the 
negotiating team of the National Union for the Total 
Independence of Angola [UNITA]. No one knows what was discussed 
during these meetings. 
  Then the negotiating teams from the government and UNITA 
went 
to the conference hall to discuss alone the document on swearing 
in UNITA members of parliament. The government presented UNITA 
a new document containing all guarantees. UNITA says it wants 
to study the document. All that is known is that the parties 
are near to reaching an agreement. 
  Meanwhile, yesterday, UNITA made an official statement 
saying 
that it accepts the government offer on its participation in 
different levels of government. The government agrees that it 
received UNITA's document, but the only thing is that it was 
astonished when it opened the envelope. UNITA says it accepts 
but it has changed all the government's proposals at the level 
of district governments. It wants to legally possess the 
districts it occupied illegally. It wants Soyo and Canfunfo. 
The government says there is time for jokes. Its offer is not 
negotiable. Either UNITA should say yes to the government offer 
without amendments or it says no. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

