<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   General Staff on Air Raid Killing 89 Pupils </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    General Staff on Air Raid Killing 89 Pupils </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0906202894 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0906202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Communique issued by the FAA General Staff in Luanda on 9 </F>
June] 
  [Text] The causes behind the unfortunate incident which 
involved an Angolan Air Force fighter aircraft in Waku Kungo at 
1220 on 6 June have been investigated. The conclusion follows: 
  The aircraft's mission was to carry out actions to support 
our land forces on the outskirts of Waku Kungo, a distance of 40 
to 50 kms. The aircraft showed a misreading in its course 
indicator. This, added to the existence of thick fog in the area 
experienced during this time of the year, hindered visual 
observation. Thus, the pilot carried out maneuvers taking the 
aircraft to the District of Waku Kungo. 
  Thinking that he was above his specific target, the pilot 
carried out the stipulated actions, hitting a school in the 
district. As a result of this involuntary incident, we lament 
the death of 89 pupils and the destruction of the school. 
  The General Staff of the Angolan Armed Forces [FAA] deepely 
regrets this very serious incident. It would like once again to 
present to the bereaved families its deepest condolences and 
promises to do everything in its power to minimize the damage 
caused. 
  [Issued] Office of the Chief of the FAA's General Staff, 
Luanda, 9 June 1994. 
  [Signed] Army General Joao Baptista de Matos, chief of the 
FAA General Staff. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

