<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Liberia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Wants OAU To Define ECOMOG Role </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Wants OAU To Define ECOMOG Role </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB0906154394 Gbarnga Radio ELRL in English 1400 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0906154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Gbarnga Radio ELRL </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Transitional State Council Chairman David Kpomakpor 
says government is to shortly call on the Organization of 
African Unity to clearly define the role of multinational 
African peacekeeping force in Liberia, ECOMOG [Economic 
Community of West African States Cease-Fire Monitoring Group]. 
Councillor Kpomakpor accused the multinational peacekeeping 
force of failing to take instruction from the transitional 
government and said the force was being indecisive in pushing 
the disarmament of the former warring factions. Councillor 
Kpomakpor squarely blamed the United Nations Observer Mission in 
Liberia and ECOMOG for the stalemate in the disarming of 
fighters because orders were not being taken from government. 
  The blame comes following warnings from the visiting U. S. 
State Department official, Prudence Bushnell, that the United 
States Government will reconsider its position on Liberia by the 
end of the month if up to about 50 percent of the arms are not 
taken away from the fighting groups in Liberia. 
  Councillor Kpomakpor, as an individual member of the State 
Council, has also registered his opposition to the formation of 
a national army by all parties to the Liberian conflict. 
Reports said NPFL [National Patriotic Front of Liberia] and 
ULIMO [United Liberation Movement for Democracy in Africa] 
representations on the State Council are in favor of the 
formation of the national army and that pronouncement by 
Councillor Kpomakpor does not represent a consensus view of the 
State Council as called for by the Cotonou Accord regarding 
decision-making. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

