<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   NADECO Supports Calls for Civil Disobedience </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NADECO Supports Calls for Civil Disobedience </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB0906220694 Paris AFP in French 2015 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0906220694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lagos, 9 Jun (AFP) -- The call by the opposition 
Campaign for Democracy [CD] for civil disobedience last week in 
Nigeria was made in agreement with the opposition National 
Democratic Coalition [NADECO]. This was disclosed this evening 
to AFP by a top NADECO official. 
  "Civil disobedience is part of NADECO's stipulated lines of 
action. The CD is helping to organize it," added the official, 
who was speaking by telephone from his hideout. 
  "For the moment, NADECO will not appear much in the 
forefront 
of the political scene, and will operate through several 
organizations, including the CD," the same source said, while 
refusing to disclose his identity. 
  The CD, which comprises nearly 40 human rights defense 
committees and associations for democracy "is affiliated to 
NADECO and closely collaborates with it," the official stated. 
  The CD had on 8 June called on Nigerians to stage a one-week 
mass protest effective 13 June to press for the rapid departure 
of the ruling military regime and the formation of a government 
by Moshood Abiola, the self-proclaimed winner of the 12 June 
1993 presidential election. 

</TEXT>

