<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abiola Declares Opposition Government; Escapes Arrest </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Abiola Declares Opposition Government; Escapes Arrest </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Concord Press Group Closed Down </H4>

<F P=102> AB1106145794 Paris AFP in English 1434 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1106145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lagos, June 11 (AFP) -- Nigerian police Saturday [11 
June] closed down the Concord press group, owned by Chief 
Moshood Abiola, the presumed winner of last June's presidential 
election who earlier in the day was placed under house arrest. 
  Around 80 policemen armed with assault rifles burst into the 
group's premises in the northern suburb of Ikeja and ordered all 
personnel out of the offices and cut off all access to the 
building, an AFP correspondent at the scene reported. 
  The Concord, the group's flagship daily, has stepped up its 
criticism of Nigeria's military regime over the past week, 
calling for the restoration of democracy and the formation of a 
government of national unity under Abiola. 
  The millionaire businessman, widely seen as having won the 
presidential poll on June 12, 1993 that was subsequently 
annulled by the regime of General Ibrahim Babangida, was 
preparing to declare an alternative government when he was 
placed under house arrest early Saturday morning. 
  The Concord group comprises around a dozen publications. 

</TEXT>

