<H4>    Kagame: Intervention To Escalate Conflict </H4>

<F P=102> LD1906142994 Paris Radio France International in French 1230 
GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1906142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Following a short lull yesterday, fighting 
resumed at dawn today in the center of Kigali with RPF [Rwandan 
Patriotic Front] forces shelling several positions held by 
government forces. [passage omitted] 
  The RPF has repeated its position that it opposes French 
intervention in Rwanda. Paul Kagame, the RPF military leader, 
said this earlier this morning when he spoke to Christophe 
Boisbouvier: 
  [Begin Kagame recording, in English fading into French 
translation] We intend to oppose the French intervention in 
this conflict by all means available to us because of the role 
played in Rwanda by the French in the past. We believe that 
they want to intervene for reasons other than those they claim, 
and we believe that UN forces on the ground can fulfill the 
mission the French want to carry out. 
  I think their presence here is going to have an escalating 
effect on the conflict; they are claiming that militias and 
government forces are murdering civilians, but they supported 
the so-called interim government responsible for all the 
massacres, so they are simply coming here to protect these 
people. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

