<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   RPF Reacts to Plans for French Intervention </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RPF Reacts to Plans for French Intervention </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    RPF Urges Mobilization Against France </H4>

<F P=102> AB1806153394 Paris AFP in English 1505 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1806153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, June 18 (AFP) -- Rebels of the Rwandan 
Patriotic Front (RPF) called on Rwandans at home and abroad 
Saturday [18 June] to "mobilise" against a French initiative to 
send a humanitarian intervention force to Rwanda. 
  "Mobilise to bring down the French treason plan. You are 
Rwandan, you must live or die in Rwanda and not elsewhere," RPF 
politburo member Jacques Bihozagara said in a statement issued 
here. 
  The appeal to "general mobilisation" also called on "African 
countries which want to follow France in carrying out its 
sinister plan" to think again. 
  "Maybe you have debts to France, but find other ways to 
repay 
them than with Rwandan blood," the statement said. 
  Earlier in the day, French President Francois Mitterrand 
told 
a meeting of the UN Educational, Scientific and Cultural 
Organisation in Paris that the setting up of the "humanitarian 
protection force", proposed by France, was a matter of "hours 
and days". 
  France also wants to involve other African countries in 
sending to Rwanda a peace-keeping force of some 1,000 to 2,000 
soldiers under UN guidance. 
  "Today, France, rounding off its plan, flies to the rescue 
of 
the executioners on the run," the RPF statement also said, 
speaking of France's alleged support for the embattled 
Hutu-dominated Rwandan government. 
  The head of the RPF [Rwandan Patriotic Front] bureau in 
Brussels, James Rwego, said the text was a "call to take up arms 
against France on Rwandan territory." 
  If French troops went to Rwanda, they would be considered "a 
hostile force," he told AFP. 
  He said the statement had been drawn up after consulting RPF 
officials in Rwanda. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

