<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   RPF Reacts to Plans for French Intervention </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RPF Reacts to Plans for French Intervention </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Intervention Termed `Act of Provocation' </H4>

<F P=102> LD1906083594 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 0700 
GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1906083594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mortar fire resounded across Kigali before dawn 
today. Heavy fighting has resumed, and small arms fire can be 
heard in the streets of the Rwandan capital. The RPF [Rwandan 
Patriotic Front] rebels are currently aiming for the 
administrative district of the city. They already hold part of 
the capital, and they are resuming the offensive to control the 
whole country. This is how we will protect the Tutsis: we do 
not need France, they repeat, even threatening France. This is 
what Jacques Bihozagara, RPF spokesman in Brussels, had to say 
to Anne-Marie Mouradian: 
  [Begin recording] [Bihozagara] The RPF agreed to 
humanitarian 
intervention, but we do not want a mission which is imposed upon 
us. For a long time, we have been opposed to a French presence 
among the blue helmets. We now see that France has decided on 
war. 
  As you know, there was a Security Council resolution that 
defined the framework for intervention by the international 
community. Now France wants to go in alone, or with its friends 
or its acolytes. France is currently mobilizing African 
countries, in particular French-speaking countries, some of 
which are not all that independent from France. We consider 
French intervention as an act of provocation, and therefore we 
will meet it with the appropriate means. 
  [Mouradian] By armed force? 
  [Bihozagara] Yes, of course. We are quite ready for a trial 
of strength, and, as I said, we are prepared to make use of all 
the means at our disposal. If we must all die, then we will 
die, but I think France will also have to pay a heavy price. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

