<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Zaire </F>
<H3> <TI>   Burundian Leaders' Presence Said Causing Insecurity </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Burundian Leaders' Presence Said Causing Insecurity </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA1906125394 Nairobi KNA in English 1000 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> EA1906125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nairobi KNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kinshasa, 19 June (PANA) -- High-ranking Burundi 
Government officials, mainly from the majority Hutu ethnic 
group, spend the night in Uvira, a small town in the Zairian 
province of South Kivu, near Bujumbura. 
  "Early in the morning, these officials return to their 
offices in Bujumbura to perform their duties", the ZAIRE NEWS 
AGENCY (AZAP) correspondent reported from Uvira Friday [17 June]. 
  The influx of Burundian refugees to the small town near Lake 
Tanganyika has created an acute shortage of accommodation. 
Hotels of the area are overbooked, said the local correspondent 
of AZAP who also spoke of insecurity problems arising from the 
presence of the top Burundi Government officials in Uvira. 
Reports indicate that up to 10,000 Rwandan refugees and 70,000 
from Burundi have flocked into South Kivu so far. 

</TEXT>

